<br>
It should still last longer than 36 seconds though.  It seems that FB is to be our major encounter or &quot;oh @#%$&quot; AA Skill.  Compare it to other classes:<br>
<br>
Enchanters - Gather Mana (Recover all mana)<br>
Necros Dire - Charm, Life Burn (Unresistable up to 4,500)<br>
Wizards - Manaburn (Unresistable up to 16,000)<br>
Magicians - Frenzied Burnout (Broken)<br>
<br>
<br>
Whats wrong with that picture.  To be honest, I often understand coding problems.. but what the hell is so hard about this?  They could just let the pet enrage and flurry for 60 seconds and forget all the rest and I'd be happy.  36 seconds out of every 8640 seconds (2 hr 24 min) seems like a sad joke unless the thing does something amazing during that time. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ugoladus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goladus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Grand Poobah Goladus</span><br>  Posts: 2236<br> <font color=#333333>(9/13/02 6:29:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=341.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://doug.feldmann.com/Sigurd.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Frenzy Burnout (Setp 4 patch)</span><hr size=1> Enchanters got a better AA in gather mana?<br>
<br>
How about the ability to team up with a cleric or shaman to refill your mana in a minute or so with <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>no limit on reuse</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->?<br>
<br>
What about how SCM3 and QS lets a mage pet-canni to increase mana regen as much as rodding?<br>
<br>
Manaburn...  sure it can crit for lots.  You do realize that a manaburn crit for 16k probably took close to 4k mana?  With SCM3 and SCF3 a wizard should easily be able to deal more than 16k with that same amount of mana.  Manaburn just crunches it all into 6 seconds, typically at a large loss in effeciency.  Manaburn can also hit resistant mobs. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ushadowmagildire.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ShadowMagi LDire</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#333333>(9/13/02 7:19:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=341.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   AAs</span><hr size=1> I'd take gather mana over FB in its current form any day of the week and twice on Sunday.  A mage with mana always has options.  Mages evaluate fights by &quot;do I have enough mana to nuke and/or heal my pet and/or chain cast enough pets to when this fight&quot;.  Assuming of course that I'm not over-run.  Also gather mana is a consistant result.<br>
<br>
The point to Manaburn is that on a raid, a wizard can get in, unload major, unresistable damage and get out.   <br>
<br>
FB still doesn't currently appear to get me anything.  Even *IF* FB worked the damage could be very random. All the skills offering something guaranteed.  FB appears to guaranteed to offer nothing currently.<br>
<br>
Oh yeah, pet cani does nothing for me in a &quot;oh @#%$&quot; situation, which was my premise.  Since mages cannot root I don't get to say &quot;wait here Mr mob while I cani up more mana&quot;.  In a raid setting, I can already pump out more than enough rods to keep 2 or 3 clerics soaked in mana and nearly dead under most situtations.  14 Rods on a full bar of mana should be enough unless I'm suppling a whole raid alone.<br>
